Once again, ESPN and the NFL are in renewed negotiations for the
former to take on the latter=E2=80=99s media assets. What=E2=80=99s changed=
 since the last time these dance partners played footsie? More linear decli=
ne, Flagship, and maybe the Draft going up for bidding, too.

John Ourand ( https://puck.news/author/john-ourand/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Vars=
ity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F10%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS=
+%282%2F10%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_t=
erm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
John Ourand ( https://puck.news/author/john-ourand/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Vars=
ity+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%282%2F10%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Varsity+-+SUBSCRIBERS=
+%282%2F10%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_t=
erm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

The NFL may be the most powerful entity in media these days, but it seems n=
ot
even the Shield is immune to the ravages of cord-cutting. It was nearly fou=
r years ago that commissioner Roger Goodell retained Goldman Sachs to look =
into selling a group of the league=E2=80=99s assets, including NFL Network,=
 NFL RedZone, NFL.com, and its fantasy business. And while the league has t=
alked to every one of its media partners about the properties since the spr=
ing of 2021, there has been little interest. ESPN had demonstrated the most=
 curiosity, but 18 months of on-again,
off-again talks had reached an impasse by the middle of last year. In Septe=
mber, as the 2024 season kicked off, the NFL folded its tent and back-burne=
red the soliciting of any such sale.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Well, the talks are back on. It=E2=80=99s too early to predict whether a de=
al will be struck, of course, but ESPN=E2=80=99s plan to launch its D.T.C. =
product, code-named Flagship, has provided some renewed momentum. The two
sides have discussed the parameters of a deal that would have ESPN take con=
trol of NFL Network and NFL RedZone. On some level, this makes sense for ES=
PN, which already programs a host of 24/7 channels, and would be able to sy=
nergize the additional programming and related costs. NFL Network and NFL R=
edZone could also help the brand=E2=80=99s negotiations with cable and sate=
llite distributors and elevate ESPN=E2=80=99s status as a preferred partner=
 with the league.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

The NFL, for all its power and glory, has never had much influence in the c=
able and satellite world. After all, in coming to market with only two line=
ar channels, the league has found itself at the mercy of traditional distri=
butors, like Comcast and DirecTV, to set the terms. That would change if NF=
L Network and NFL RedZone are matched up with ABC and ESPN. While cord-cutt=
ing has hit league-owned networks especially hard, it=E2=80=99s unlikely th=
at NFL Network
and NFL RedZone would act as a drag on ESPN=E2=80=99s bundled channels, esp=
ecially since NFLN carries eight live games a year and RedZone has become a=
 popular upsell to push consumers into more expensive tiers.

More importantly for ESPN, the NFL channels add programming to Flagship, wh=
ich is expected to launch this fall. The NFL=E2=80=99s fantasy offering, wh=
ich would also be part of the deal, would be a big attraction as well. (Spo=
rts betting is expected to
play a major role in Flagship=E2=80=99s launch.) Meanwhile, this exit oppor=
tunity would unburden the NFL from carrying a rare declining asset on its b=
alance sheet. NFL Network, indeed, has been in cost-cutting mode for at lea=
st the past year, even moving its beloved daytime show, Good Morning Footba=
ll, from New York to Los Angeles to save a couple extra pennies.

Negotiations for the media assets have also coincided with talks regarding =
the NFL Draft, which the league
has put up for bid starting in 2026. Thus far, the draft has received a lot=
 of interest. ESPN, Fox, and Google/YouTube all submitted bids months ago, =
but the NFL has yet to make a move. All sides expect developments in the co=
ming weeks.

